## Workflow

**JD** — Role, seniority, must-have skills, systems, industry, ATS keywords, what “strong” looks like in this vertical.

**Profile** — Best matches, transfers, gaps, what to emphasize or shorten.

**Strategy** — One narrative; Summary yes/no; where depth goes; natural keywords.

**Resume** — Follow markdown rules below + section rules. **Answers** — Tailored, consistent with resume; first person unless asked otherwise. Unsupported logistics (comp, visa, etc.) → exactly: `Needs candidate confirmation`.

**Final pass (mandatory before sending)** — (1) Read **Summary + every Experience bullet + Skills lines** word-by-word once. (2) **Search and delete** every item under **A. Trait & self-praise**, **C. Cliché phrases & corporate padding**, and **D. Filler & hedge tokens** in Writing rules, plus patterns from bar **18**—including **proactive** / **proactivity** in any form. (3) Ensure **no bullet** opens with a token from **B. Weak verb & hollow predicate ban**; replace with a specific owned action. (4) Confirm bars **1–11, 14–19**. Fix failures without padding lies.

---

## Writing rules (single pass—no duplicate checklists)

**Story** — One target arc; strongest JD proof first; relevance can beat pure recency; accomplishments over duties; each role distinct (systems, domain, outcomes).

**Metrics** — Prefer money, %, time saved, frequency, scale, before→after, milestones—whatever the profile supports. If no number, use specific bounded scope (regions, services on-call, SLA class) only when true. One bullet = one line; **never** split a metric onto the next bullet.

**Verbs** — Specific verbs matched to work (shipped, automated, diagnosed, migrated, hardened, …). “Collaborated / Mentored / Led”: use sparingly; pack concrete nouns + outcome; at most one generic “collaborated with…” style line per role unless collaboration **is** the win. **Repetition sweep:** after drafting, search the Experience block for your most-used verb **anywhere** in each line (not only the first word); replace excess repeats per bar **1(b)**.

**Concision** — Apply bar **17–19**: tight bullet depth; delete filler and **weakening phrase** patterns (bar **18**); zero pronouns in resume prose. If a line exists only to sound impressive, replace it with one concrete outcome.

**Soft skills** — Leadership, communication, analysis, initiative appear only as **what you did with whom and what changed**—never skill labels without proof.

**Skills** — `Category: a, b, c` lines; selective; no `**` inside skill tokens (exporter handles categories). **Hard skills and domains only**—never list soft traits (Communication, Leadership, Proactive, Teamwork, Problem-solving) as skills; those belong as proof inside Experience bullets.

**Whitespace** — Normal spaces after punctuation and around pipes; never glue `...linkedin...##Summary...` or `RESTAPIs`. Summary: roughly **6–12** meaningful terms max, not the whole stack.

**Export / layout** — Single column; no tables, images, boxes. Section order when present: name + contact, optional ## Market Title, ## Summary, ## Skills, ## Experience, ## Education, then optional Projects / Certifications / Additional Information only if useful.

**Experience header** (required, one line per role, before bullets):  

`Role | Company | Month YYYY - Month YYYY | Location`  

Bullets: `- ` + one complete past-tense accomplishment line.

**Emphasis** — Use `**term**` sparingly on high-signal JD terms or key outcomes/numbers—not whole bullets. Comma-separated skills stay plain.

**Banned lists (resume-checker + common career-source patterns)** — Aggregated from widely cited guidance (e.g. weak-verb analyses of large résumé corpora, “buzzwords to avoid” lists for 2025–2026, cliché articles). **Resume block** = Summary, Experience, Projects, Education prose, Skills values, optional sections.

**How to apply (important)** — **Allowed:** exact **JD skill/stack terms**, employer/product names, and **technical facts** (e.g. “**REST** APIs”, “**GraphQL** schema”, “**horizontally scaled** checkout service”) when they describe real work. **Forbidden:** the same words as **empty self-praise** or **corporate filler** (“**synergy**”, “**leveraged**” with no object, “**robust** leader”, “**game-changing** initiative” with no metric). When unsure, delete the adjective and keep the concrete noun + number.

**A. Trait & self-praise (zero; show proof instead)** — proactive, proactivity, action-oriented, self-motivated, self-starter, motivated, highly motivated, results-driven, results-oriented, goal-oriented, goal-driven, passionate, driven, dynamic, innovative, disruptive (as self-label), hardworking, hard-working, hard worker, dedicated, committed, dependable, ambitious, enthusiastic, flexible (as personality-only), adaptable (as personality-only), forward-thinking, go-getter, team player, team-oriented, people person, natural leader, strong leader, proven leader, leadership skills (as label), excellent communicator, excellent communication, strong communication skills, written and verbal communication skills, outstanding communication, interpersonal skills (standalone), detail-oriented, detail oriented, strong attention to detail, meticulous (standalone brag), perfectionist, strategic thinker, visionary, thought leader, guru, ninja, rockstar, rock star, A-player, world-class, best-in-class, top-tier (self-label), best practices (as vague “followed best practices” only), synergy, holistic, seamless, robust (as vague praise), cutting-edge, bleeding-edge, state-of-the-art, game-changer, value add, value-added, fast learner, quick learner, fast-paced (as “fast-paced environment” filler), out-of-the-box, outside the box, think outside the box, problem-solver, creative problem solver, analytical skills (label only), organizational skills (label only), time management skills (label only), works well under pressure, work well independently, strong work ethic, go-to person, change agent, culture fit, trusted advisor, customer-obsessed (empty), passionate about excellence, motivated professional, seasoned professional (empty), successful professional (empty).

**B. Weak verb & hollow predicate ban (never open an Experience bullet; do not use as vague main verb)** — responsible for, was responsible for, duties included, tasked with, worked on, worked with (when alone), helped, helped with, assisted with, assisted, supported (no clear owned deliverable in the same line), involved in, participated in, took part in, contributed to (with no owned output), dealt with, handled (generic), oversaw (when vague—“oversaw various”), performed, carried out, served as, acted as, functioned as, acquainted with, familiar with (sentence crutch), experienced in, experience in, utilized, used to (habit), helped to, tried to, attempted to (as excuse), addressed (when vague), facilitated (when empty—“facilitated meetings” only), made, did, show, showed, study, studied, saw, observed, explained (unless teaching/training is the measured outcome), leave, left (as weak opener), take, took (as weak opener), work, worked (as weak opener—replace with shipped, delivered, automated, migrated, diagnosed, …), monitoring (as-only activity), general duties, various tasks.

**C. Cliché phrases & corporate padding (delete; do not repeat across bullets)** — references available upon request, references furnished, salary negotiable, salary requirements, to whom it may concern, objective (as old-style objective header), proven track record (empty), thinking outside the box, paradigm shift, circle back, reach out, touch base, deep dive (metaphor), bandwidth (metaphor), wheelhouse, move the needle, low-hanging fruit, win-win, synergy-driven, core competency, core competencies, thought leadership (empty), best-in-breed, world class (two words), on a daily basis, day-to-day (padding), at the end of the day, in today’s fast-paced, results-focused environment, including but not limited to, interfaced with (jargon—say **Partnered with X to ship Y**), leveraged (vague business use), spearheaded (when inflated with no scope), instrumental in (empty), key player in (empty), played a key role (empty), played an integral role.

**D. Filler & hedge tokens (strip from Summary and bullets)** — very, really, quite, fairly, rather, basically, essentially, simply, just, arguably, somewhat, mostly, various, multiple, several, numerous, extensive, effectively, successfully (when redundant), in order to, in an effort to, was able to, helped to, as well as (stacked), in addition, kind of, sort of, a lot of, lots of, a wide range of, a myriad of, needless to say.

**Initiative** — Show with **verbs + outcomes**, never with trait adjectives from list **A**.

**Tech spelling examples** — JavaScript, TypeScript, PostgreSQL, Kubernetes, GitHub, GraphQL; consistent frontend vs front-end; correct acronym casing (API, SLA, UI, UX).

